8:[["$","main",null,{"className":"px-4 md:px-0","children":[["$","section",null,{"children":[["$","h1",null,{"className":"font-semibold tracking-tight text-4xl text-slate-900","children":"Underneath the component: theme driven design systems"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-slate-500 text-sm tracking-tight font-mono block mt-4","children":["Published on"," ",["$","time",null,{"dateTime":"2019-01-04","children":"4 Jan 2019"}]]}]]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"py-5","children":["$","article",null,{"className":"prose prose-lg","children":"$L13"}]}]]}],["$","script",null,{"type":"application/ld+json","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"{\"@context\":\"https://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"BlogPosting\",\"headline\":\"Underneath the component: theme driven design systems\",\"url\":\"https://saurabhcoded.github.io/posts/theme-driven-design-systems\",\"datePublished\":\"2019-01-04\",\"dateModified\":\"2019-01-04\",\"author\":[{\"@type\":\"Person\",\"name\":\"Saurabh Sharma\",\"url\":\"https://saurabhcoded.github.io\"}]}"}}]]
13:[["$","p",null,{"children":"“Buttons, inputs, typography“. The foundations of any design system right? As engineers and designers, it often helps us to break up a user interface in to a collection of smaller parts. Whether these manifest as symbols in our design tools, or components in our codebases, these smaller chunks are often used as the grounds for a UI system."}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":"However if we dig deeper, we can still find shared patterns among these components, whether it be font sizing, or spacing, or colour."}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["As an example, we can breakdown a web dropdown (",["$","code",null,{"children":"<select>"}],") in to some primitive values:"]}],"\n",["$","ul",null,{"children":["\n",["$","li",null,{"children":["the font sizing of the placeholder (",["$","code",null,{"children":"14px"}],")"]}],"\n",["$","li",null,{"children":["the background color of the box (",["$","code",null,{"children":"#fff"}],")"]}],"\n",["$","li",null,{"children":["the border style of the box (",["$","code",null,{"children":"1px solid #cfd8df"}],")"]}],"\n"]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":"These values are often the same across multiple components. For example, the border color of a dropdown on hover, will likely be the same as the border color of a text input or checkbox on hover."}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/posts/2019-01-04-theme-driven-design-systems/component-tokens.png","alt":"Shared tokens across an input, dropdown, checkbox, and radio button"}]}],"\n",["$","h2",null,{"children":"Encouraging experimentation"}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":"Thinking about our components as compositions of these values, helps us to not only begin to consider how we can remove duplication (to keep our code DRYer), but also encourages us to create more open systems."}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":"One of the hardest part of building a good UI system, is finding the balance between providing a baseline for others to work from and being too restrictive."}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":"Defining components as the lowest elements of a system provides little room for experimentation without either creating variants of an existing component; composing existing components to make a new larger component; or creating an entirely new component. It's here that divergence often happens."}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":"These values (often referred to as 'design tokens'), provide a nice route to opt out of the provided components, but still remain within the bounds of the system. For example, an engineer may want to build a variant of an input, that although visually looks similar to a normal input, may have a wildly different technical implementation."}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":"Consider the following two components. Although both the wrapping containers are visually similar, they must have two separate implementations to allow for the second component to contain non-text content."}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/posts/2019-01-04-theme-driven-design-systems/multiple-implementations-visually-similar-component.png","alt":"Two implementations of two visually similar inputs"}]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":"The implementation of the first component might be as simple as:"}],"\n",["$","pre",null,{"children":["$","code",null,{"className":"hljs language-html","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"hljs-tag","children":["<",["$","span",null,{"className":"hljs-name","children":"input"}]," ",["$","span",null,{"className":"hljs-attr","children":"type"}],"=",["$","span",null,{"className":"hljs-string","children":"\"text\""}]," ",["$","span",null,{"className":"hljs-attr","children":"value"}],"=",["$","span",null,{"className":"hljs-string","children":"\"Alex James\""}]," ",["$","span",null,{"className":"hljs-attr","children":"class"}],"=","$L14"," />"]}],"\n"]}]}],"\n","$L15","\n","$L16","\n","$L17","\n","$L18","\n","$L19","\n","$L1a","\n","$L1b","\n","$L1c","\n","$L1d","\n","$L1e","\n","$L1f","\n","$L20","\n","$L21","\n","$L22","\n","$L23","\n","$L24","\n","$L25","\n","$L26","\n","$L27","\n","$L28","\n","$L29","\n","$L2a","\n","$L2b","\n","$L2c"]
